The Democratic Alliance (DA) the Western Cape says it supports Premier Alan Winde’s call for national government to amend the current lockdown regulations. DA provincial leader, Bonginkosi Madikizela, says the latest data has confirmed that the province has passed its peak and active coronavirus cases are declining. He says government must now focus on rescuing the economy. Winde says, “We supported some of these measures during the height of the festive season when our health facilities were under pressure and our health care workers could not cope.  We’ve now seen the devastation in our economy and we’re calling for the national government to relax these regulations, so that we can create much-needed jobs and bring back the dignity of our people.” SABC News’ Mariska Botha reports that Western Cape has passed its peak: Small businesses Many small businesses in townships in the Western Cape are battling to survive in the midst of the second wave of the COVID-19 pandemic. In the video below, local authorities are looking at ways to help small businesses stay afloat: INFOGRAPHIC: Amended lockdown level 3 regulations sabcnews.com | SABC News channel | SABC Radio news SA COVID-19 AMENDED LEVEL 3 LOCKDOWN REGULATIONS MASKS The wearing of a face mask is mandatory for every  person when in a public place. Public places include the workplace, public transport and retail stores.   Any person who does not wear a mask in public will be committing an offence. On conviction, they will be liable to a fine or imprisonment for a period not exceeding six months or to both a fine and imprisonment.  CURFEW Every person is confined to his or her place of residence from 9PM until 5AM daily, unless a person: Has been granted permission through directions by the relevant Cabinet member or a permit to perform a service. Is attending to a security or medical emergency GATHERINGS 1.5 metres Every business premises must determine the maximum number of staff and customers permitted at any one time while maintaining a distance of 1.5 metres between people.H   Health protocols must be observed at gatherings, including maintaining a distance of at least 1.5 metres between people.  Attendance of a funeral is limited to a maximum of 50 persons.  If the venue is too small to hold 50 persons observing a distance of at least one and a half metres from each other. then not more than 50 percent of the capacity of the venue may be used.   Night vigils and after-funeral gatherings "after- tears" are not allowed.  The duration of a funeral is restricted to a maximum of two hours.  HRS FUNERALS Closing time for non-essential establishments, whether indoors or outdoors, is 20H00. This includes restaurants and bars. 20h00 Indoor and outdoor social gatherings, religious gatherings, political events, traditional council meetings and gatherings at sports grounds are prohibited.  Where there are exceptions, such as restauranrs, museums and gyms, no more than 50 people are permitted indoors and no more than 100 people outdoors- and may not exceed more than 50% of a venue's capacity.  All beaches, dams, lakes, rivers, public parks and public swimming pools in hotspot areas will be closed to the public. AMENDED LEVEL 3 AMENDED LEVEL 3 AMENDED LEVEL 3 AS ANNOUNCED ON 11 JANUARY 2021 Botanical gardens, national parks and other parks where access control measures and entry limitations may remain open to the public. sabcnews.com | SABC News channel | SABC Radio news Source: South African government sabcnews.com | SABC News channel | SABC Radio news Source: South African government 20 land ports of entry will be closed until 15 February 2021 for general entry and departure.  BORDERS AMENDED LEVEL 3 The sale, dispensing, and distribution of liquor for off-site consumption and for on-site consumption is prohibited.    Alcohol sales from retail outlets are not permitted.   ALCOHOL Beitbridge Lebombo Maseru Bridge Oshoek Ficksburg Kopfontein  CLOSED BORDERS - transportation of fuel, ca